\v 20 Now after many years, when it pleased God, Nehemiah, having received a charge from the king of Persia, sent in quest of the fire the descendants of the priests that hid it. When they declared to us that they had found no fire, but thick water,
\v 21 he commanded them to draw out thereof and bring \add to him:\add* and when \f + \fr 1:21 \ft Gr. \fqa the things of the sacrifices.\ft Similarily in verses 31, 33, and 2 Maccabees 2:10. \f* the sacrifices had been offered\add on the altar, \add* Nehemiah commanded the priests to sprinkle with the water both the wood and the things laid thereupon.
\v 22 And when it was done, and some time had passed, and the sun shone out, which before was hid with clouds, there was kindled a great blaze, so that all men marveled.
\v 23 And the priests made a prayer while the sacrifice was consuming, both the priests and all\add others, \add* Jonathan leading and the rest answering, as Nehemiah did.
\v 24 And the prayer was after this manner:
\p O Lord, Lord God, the Creator of all things, who are terrible and strong and righteous and merciful, who alone are King and gracious,
\v 25 who alone supply \add every need, \add* who alone are righteous and almighty and eternal, you that save Israel out of all evil, who made the fathers \add your \add* chosen, and did sanctify them:
\v 26 accept the sacrifice for all your people Israel, and guard your own portion, and consecrate it.
\v 27 Gather together our Dispersion, set at liberty those who are in bondage among the heathen, look upon those who are despised and abhorred, and let the heathen know that you are our God.
\v 28 Torment those who oppress us and in arrogance shamefully entreat us.
\v 29 Plant your people in your holy place, even as Moses said.
